```

What "Done" Looks Like
When Phase 1 is complete, I should be able to:
1. ✅ Run `npm run dev` and see the placeholder page
2. ✅ Toggle the grid overlay and see the 12-column structure
3. ✅ Toggle dark/light mode with smooth transitions
4. ✅ See Space Grotesk at display sizes, Inter for body text, JetBrains Mono for technical labels
5. ✅ See the full type scale from display-xl down to caption
6. ✅ See the color system (backgrounds, text hierarchy, accent)
7. ✅ See a grid violation (text bleeding past margins)
8. ✅ See responsive behavior on mobile (4-col), tablet (8-col), desktop (12-col)
9. ✅ See the accent color used sparingly and intentionally
This is the foundation. Everything else builds on top of it. Don't skip ahead to fancy features — get the bones right.
Notes for Claude Code
* Don't use `next-themes` package — the custom ThemeProvider above is simpler and gives us more control over the transition. If you already installed it, that's fine, just don't use it.
* Tailwind dynamic classes: The `col-span-${n}` pattern in GridItem won't work with Tailwind's JIT compiler. Use a safelist in the config OR switch to inline styles for grid placement. Prefer inline styles: `style={{ gridColumn: \`${start} / span ${span}` }}`.
* Font loading: If Space Grotesk feels too narrow/quirky once rendered, General Sans (from Fontshare) is the backup. But try Space Grotesk first.
* The placeholder page is disposable — it exists only to verify the design system. We'll replace it with the real landing page in Phase 2.

